 :tx/rationale "ADVERSARIAL AUDIT PASS — trying to break the Session-Aware Guidance design. Questions: (1) What if agent runs braid go on 20 tasks? Working set becomes 20 — still too large for meaningful boost. ANSWER: This is legitimate behavior (batch claiming). The 3.0x boost still differentiates these 20 from the other 280+ open tasks. At 20 active tasks, the boost gives them 3x advantage — meaningful. Only problematic at 100+ active, which is pathological. (2) What if no harvest ever happened AND no session entity? session_boundary = now - 3600. But what if the session is longer than 1 hour? Tasks claimed 2 hours ago get NO boost. ANSWER: The 1-hour fallback is deliberately conservative — it's the worst case. Most sessions are 1-4 hours. A 2-hour-old claim not getting boosted means the agent should re-claim (braid go) to refresh. This is actually DESIRABLE behavior — stale claims should decay. (3) What about EPIC siblings when the EPIC has 50 children? All 50 get 2.0x. ANSWER: This is correct — EPIC siblings are semantically related. If you're working on EPIC X, all its children are relevant context. (4) What if the retrospective data is poisoned by a session where the agent deliberately ignored all recommendations? Accuracy = 0.0, which pulls boost_scale down. ANSWER: Grid search finds the MEAN-optimal scale — one outlier session doesn't dominate. With 5+ sessions, one zero-accuracy session contributes 1/5 of the signal. ROBUST. (5) What if session_boundary computation is expensive? Three queries: find_active_session, last_harvest_wall_time, SystemTime::now. All O(n) over datoms. At 15K datoms, this is <1ms. NOT expensive. CONCLUSION: Design is sound after temporal discrimination fix. No further revisions needed."
